1156	I.B.M. thinks it can make real, predictable improvements in technology services.	https://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/26/blogs/26bits-a-moores4687.html	Could there be a kind of Moore's Law that would cover predictable advancement in complex technology consulting services?  It's a question that people familiar with the services business might find comical and perplexing. Services engagements are called engagements for a reason. They're often one-off hand-holding proposals with indefinite ends.   So it seems tough for a company to claim any type of consistent improvement in services performance where a client could expect to see, say, twice as much efficiency every couple of years.   But I.B.M. -- who else? -- believes a Moore's Law equivalent is achievable with so-called service systems. And the man pushing the idea is Jim Spohrer, the director of services research at I.B.M.'s Almaden research facility in San Jose, Calif.   That's right. Here comes Spohrer's Law.   In industry parlance, a service system could be anything from a company to a university, a government body or a water management plant. It's really any type of semi-complex organization.   I.B.M.'s big push these days revolves around making these types of service systems smarter. You may have seen the ads.   Mr. Spohrer estimates that the planet holds about six trillion service systems, and I.B.M. wants to find out how they all interact. Rather bluntly, I.B.M. would like to create a computer model of all the service systems and begin running algorithms across the model to determine, for example, how a change in the price of toasters in China affects people in other countries who supply the metal used for the toaster's paneling, and others who produce the plastic, and so on.   We build these very, very complex systems, and they have these unintended consequences we didn't foresee, Mr. Spohrer said. We have to design systems that are more self-correcting and that can learn.  With something like water management, I.B.M. argues that it could start off by trying to make sure that a given system worked well and that purification processes functioned as expected. With that job done, I.B.M. could then turn to look at how people's use of things like dishwashers and washing machines matched up with energy prices, and try to offer advice on when people should run such devices. Further out, Mr. Spohrer said, I.B.M. could dig into how the water management system affected local ecosystems: Are the frogs and the fish happy?   The bigger idea here is that I.B.M. could try to put some type of measurement around the short-term and long-term effects of changes to a service system.   The Moore's Law part will be about increasing the percent of win-win interactions, Mr. Spohrer said.  He points to the global financial meltdown as proof that the world's financial service systems are now tightly interwoven.   By studying such interactions and making quick changes, I.B.M. proposes that it could help smooth out the ups and downs of market shifts.   Such talk sounds borderline techno-utopian, although Mr. Spohrer dismisses that notion.   It isn't that I have a perfect model, and everything is going to be perfect, he said. It's that there is quite a bit of anarchy and uncertainty, but we can still make statistical statements about these systems and how quickly they can recover.  I.B.M. has about 500 people dedicated to services research and has tested out some of its ideas on the company's own business.   For example, I.B.M.'s researchers developed an automated system for improving large online technology purchases. While about 90 percent of the orders are button-pushing affairs, some of the more complex deals require customers to enter specific information about the products and services they want. Some of I.B.M.'s services software would use semantic and syntactic checks to review the customer orders.   We could flag things that customers didn't do properly, Mr. Spohrer said. Using this technology, you can shift revenue forward on the order of $100 million per year because mistakes with the complex deals often take time to resolve. 	2009-03-26T11:01:21+0000	None	Blogs	Web Log	643
