2083	 DESIGN -- Choosing among hundreds of old scientific instruments, students at Middlebury College will catalog and curate a museum exhibit this month in a winter term course, 'Early Scientific Instruments: Exhibiting Artifacts From Middlebury's First Century.'    TOOLS -- Even in a world of digital readouts and nanoseconds, many of these brass, wood and glass instruments remain useful for teaching. This includes a device (pictured) that knocks a playing card out from under a ball that stays in place, demonstrating the principle of inertia. 'It's less messy than the tablecloth version of the trick,' says Fred Winkler, a physicist who is team-teaching with Ken Pohlman, a designer at the Middlebury College Museum of Art, which will display the exhibit.    EDUCATIONAL VALUE -- The course will ask: Where did these instruments come from, who built them, using what materials? What is the science that was being taught with them? Students will also learn how to 'get a simple idea across, without insulting the expert while educating the layman,' Mr. Pohlman says. And they will master 'how to write a label.'    CONTEXT -- More colleges are adding winter terms, usually with an interdisciplinary thrust to bring together students from different fields. Courses are often unconventional: DePauw University is offering 'Baseball as a Manifestation of 20th-Century History and Culture'; the University of South Alabama has 'Introduction to Wedding Photography.' Middlebury offers more than 100 winter term courses; freshmen and sophomores must take one each winter. Classes meet 12 hours a week for four weeks. They do make for a shorter vacation -- two weeks instead of the typical four to six. But Middlebury, at least, has its own ski area, the Snow Bowl.	https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/08/us/education/syllabus-science-then-and-now.html	Correction Appended	2006-01-08T05:00:00+0000	Education Life Supplement	U.S.	News	362
