2229	Why start worrying now about scientists pushing a political agenda?	https://tierneylab.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/02/27/blogs/27tierneylab-politici523.html	Why start worrying now about scientists pushing a political agenda? That question was raised by many critics of my Findings column and blog post about Roger Pielke Jr.'s book on the roles of scientists in making policy, The Honest Broker. Wasn't it disingenuous, the critics asked, to worry about the politicization of science now instead of during the Bush administration?   I agree that there were lots of attempts to use science for political ends during the Bush years. I wrote about some of the questionable claims by the Drug Enforcement Administration and the White House drug czar's office. In his book, Dr. Pielke devotes a chapter to the Bush's administration manipulation of expert conclusions on Iraq's weapons of mass destruction. The politicization of science is clearly a bipartisan affair, and I don't think Republicans are any less prone to this problem than Democrats.  But I do think that this problem may be more difficult to spot when the Democrats are in power, simply because so many scientists are personally sympathetic to Democratic policies. Surveys and exit polls have found a preponderance of Democrats among academics and Ph.D.s. However much they try to be impartial, they're prone to the confirmation bias, which makes them less skeptical of results and statements that jibe with their own beliefs.   Some readers also complained that I was unfair in my column in questioning warnings made by Steven Chu, the new secretary of energy, and John Holdren, the nominee for presidential science adviser. Stewart commented:    . . . you do not indicate whether either Dr. Chu or Dr. Holdren misrepresent the current state of knowledge or concern among scientists in the areas they are speaking about. If what they say is uncomfortable, but represents the consensus, then we have good reason to be discomforted and act. If they offend some political scientists (not scientists, but laymen in science, who clearly have agendas), then tough. What are the current predictions for California's water supply over the next 100 years (in a word, dire). What is the carrying capacity of the Earth, in the best judgement of the most qualified group?   Let's look at the warning I cited from Dr. Chu, which came an interview with Jim Tankersley (whose article about it ran in the the Los Angeles Times and other newspapers). He discusses a future climate scenario in which, due to a failure to restrict carbon emissions, the snow pack in the California mountains declines by 70 to 90 percent by the end of the century. When asked if this means California would be looking at a scenario of permanent water rationing, Dr. Chu replies:   No, you're looking at a scenario where there's no more agriculture in California. When you lose 70 percent of your water in the mountains, I don't see how agriculture can continue. California produces 20 percent of the agriculture in the United States. I don't actually see how they can keep their cities going.   This strikes me as problematic for several reasons. First, it's based on computer models of regional climate change, which are far less reliable than models of global change. But even if you accept the model, even if you assume the snow pack essentially disappears, it doesn't follow that California's agriculture and cities would also disappear -- and Dr. Chu's scientific training in atomic physics doesn't give him any special foresight on this question. He is not an expert in agriculture or water-supply management or urban economics.   Before Californians abandoned all their farms and homes, they'd certainly consider alternate sources of water -- like, say, the Pacific Ocean. The use of desalinated water has grown rapidly in America in recent years and is projected to become increasingly cost-effective, according to recent reports from the National Research Council and a state task force in California. If technology keeps improving and people getting richer, it could become more and more affordable.  Now, I have no idea how cheap or plentiful desalinated water will be in California at the end of this century -- for all I know, Californians will still be drinking runoff from the snow in the mountains, or they'll have found other ways to conserve or import enough water for their needs. Nor do I minimize the possibility that climate change could affect the current water supply system. My point is simply that there are plenty of ways for Californians to prevent their state from becoming an empty desert, and that I'm skeptical of an expert's warning that the state will become a wasteland in 2090 unless we all quickly adopt his carbon-cutting strategies. It reminds me of the past mistaken prophecies of doom from the Club of Rome and other supposed experts who failed to anticipate the adaptability of humans.   In Dr. Holdren's confirmation hearing in the Senate, he was asked by Senator David Vitter, a Republican from Louisiana, about some of the massive famines and other disasters he had envisioned, like his 1971 warning (issued together with the ecologist Paul Ehrlich) that some form of eco-catastrophe, if not thermonuclear war, seems almost certain to overtake us before the end of the century. Was that a responsible prediction, Mr. Vitter asked?  Dr. Holdren replied that one of the things I've learned in the intervening nearly four decades is that predictions about the future are difficult.   He defended his past warnings by saying, I would argue that the motivation for looking at the downside possibilities, the possibilities that can go wrong, is to motivate people to change directions.  What do you think of that argument?   (Dr. Pielke Jr. has some thoughts at the Prometheus blog on doomsaying scientists and other questions raised by my column about his book.) 	2009-02-27T20:23:39+0000	None	Blogs	Web Log	948
