2298	Denise Grady answered select reader questions on her article about a new laser technique for treating brain aneurysms from this week's Science Times.    Q. How was the bleeding kept under control after the laser made the cut in the artery? Why did Dr. Langer not use an artery from the chest [as is done in heart by pass surgery] for the bypass? A vein is more likely to get clogged up after a few years. - I. Jochelman    A. An open end of a segment of vein was sewn to the wall of the brain artery, making a sort of a T junction. Then, the laser was slipped into the vein and put flush up against the artery wall to make the hole. Then, as you suspect, the artery does bleed through the hole. But the laser is taken out quickly, and the vein is clamped. This does not affect blood flow in the artery. Later, after the vein is joined to the vein that has been sewn into the neck, completing the bypass, the clamp is removed.    Q. Before you revealed Dr. Tulleken's technique, I was thinking, why don't they just do the graft first? I just assumed it would be much like performing a heart bypass. So the question is---why hasn't neurosurgery always used a non-tie-off approach to manage aneurysm? Also, I don't quite understand the significance of the laser. Does it create a connection site for the graft that is not otherwise possible? Finally, does the procedure have a name? Thanks very much. -- J. Westropp    A. As the article mentions, if you cut the hole in the artery first, there will be too much bleeding. You have to clamp. If you sew on the vein graft first, how do you get to the artery to cut the hole? This is what the laser does: as the story says, they can slip into the vein to make the hole.  	https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/22/health/science/ask-science.html	Denise Grady answered select reader questions on her article about a new laser technique for treating brain aneurysms from this week's Science Times.	2006-12-22T05:00:00+0000	Science Desk	Health	Question	762
