2346	Gerald Jonas reviews following books: Spaceland by Rudy Rucker; Schild's Ladder by Greg Egan; and Empire of Bones by Liz Williams (M)	https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/16/books/science-fiction.html	In 1884, an English schoolmaster named Edwin A. Abbott wrote a short book called 'Flatland: A Romance of Many Dimensions.' Although Abbott's academic specialty was classics, not mathematics, he set out to describe what life might be like for creatures who lived in a two-dimensional world. The result is a charming brainteaser that challenges inhabitants of what Abbott called Spaceland -- that is, our three-dimensional world -- to imagine an existence strictly delimited by plane geometry. 'Flatland,' which is still in print, purports to be the memoirs of A. Square, who has the dubious fortune to spend 24 hours in Spaceland yet cannot convince his 2-D compatriots that reality extends beyond their familiar plane of existence.	2002-06-16T05:00:00+0000	Book Review Desk	Books	Review	1097
