2349	Gerald Jonas reviews following books: Coyote by Allen M Steele; The Poison Master by Liz Williams; Jubilee by Jack Dann; and Worlds Enough & Time by Dan Simmons (M)	https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/05/books/science-fiction.html	COYOTE (Ace, $23.95), by Allen M. Steele, is full of pleasant surprises. It is actually three books in one, each a bracing turn on a genre staple. The first story is a near-future political thriller in which a right-wing coup has resulted in the overthrow of the constitutional government of the United States, erecting a fascist state called the United Republic of America. To awe its enemies, the republic decides to colonize a recently discovered Earth-type planet called Coyote. But a group of rebels, led by conspirators within the government's space program, plans to hijack the transport spaceship and replace the government's hand-picked colonists with 100 leading dissidents and their families. Steele manages to wring considerable suspense from this scenario, which reads like an updated version of Sinclair Lewis's antifascist novel of 1935, 'It Can't Happen Here.'	2003-01-05T05:00:00+0000	Book Review Desk	Books	Review	1134
