s being donated or sold to developing nations by recycling businesses in the United States as a way to dodge the expense of having to recycle it properly. The report, prepared by the Basel Action Network of Seattle, focuses on Nigeria, in western Africa, but says the situation is similar throughout much of the developing world. [C5.]    Movie Directors Bring New Skill to Video Games  The line between movies and video games is blurring. Major movie studios, with libraries of movies, want to make video games, and video game makers see potential in movies. And now a new generation of movie directors who grew up playing video games are bringing their storytelling skills to that world. [C1.]    Cisco Develops Technology for Radio Communication  Cisco Systems plans to announce a new method for marrying the frequently incompatible radio gear used by emergency service agencies and businesses, using an Internet telephone standard. The approach is aimed at connecting the diverse array of push-to-talk radio systems with other voice and data systems without the expense of replacing the existing systems. [C5.]    Consumer Blogs Get Attention From Product Makers  As the number of blogs has grown, more consumers are keeping Web diaries dedicated exclusively to their favorite brands. Most of these, like one maintained by Darren Rovell, left, who compiles articles and commentary on Gatorade, are done without the consent of the companies that own the brands, but some companies are starting to pay attention, using the blogs as a kind of informal network of consumer opinion. [C6.]    Criticism of Yahoo Disclosure in China Rises  Yahoo has suffered a good deal of opprobrium since it was revealed last month that, when government officials came calling, the company's Hong Kong division simply surrendered information on a Chinese citizen who had presumably sought anonymity in a Yahoo e-mail address. Yahoo contends that it must obey the laws of the land in which it operates, but the online 