r Independent Pictures division of Warner Brothers, has resigned. After a slow start in 2003, the specialty unit enjoyed success last year, notably with the documentary 'March of the Penguins.' [C13.]    DOWNBEAT FORECAST -- Electronic Arts, the video game publishing giant, delivered a bleak outlook for its coming fiscal year. The company said it expected to earn 35 cents to 65 cents a share during its 2007 fiscal year, which ends next March 31. Wall Street analysts had expected a profit of $1.07 a share. [C5.]    DELAY OF GAME -- Electronic Arts will have plenty of sports and combat offerings next week at E3, the video game convention in Los Angeles. What it will not have are many games made for the eagerly awaited Sony PlayStation 3. [E1.]    STOCKS DECLINE  -- Shares dipped after strong economic data renewed concerns about interest rates and an outlook by Procter & Gamble missed expectations. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16.17 points, to 11,400.28. The Standard & Poor's 500-stock index fell 5.36 points, to 1,307.85. The Nasdaq composite index declined 5.87 points, to 2,303.97. [C15.]    ENRON TRIAL -- Defense lawyers in the Enron trial called on two accounting specialists to counter prosecution claims that the company had falsified its books. Testimony continues today with closing arguments expected to start May 15.[C4.]    AIRLINE AGREEMENT -- The union representing pilots at Northwest Airlines said they ratified a labor contract that would save the airline $358 million a year and avert a possible strike. [C7.]    DEUTSCHE BANK PROFIT -- Deutsche Bank, Germany's biggest bank, said first-quarter profit and revenue rose, with its investment arm reaping gains from good market conditions. Earnings rose nearly 55 percent, to 1.7 billion euros ($2.15 billion), or 3.3 euros ($4.17) a share. [C6.]    ONLINE    UNWIRING THE RESERVATION: An audio slide show discusses how the Pala Indian community has connected residents with a Wi-Fi network. It is at nytimes.com/