4574	The Senate health committee on Wednesday will complete its drafting of legislation to revamp the American health care system, the first of three major health care bills to be voted out of committee.	https://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/07/15/blogs/15thecaucus-senate-h33323.html	The Senate health committee on Wednesday will complete its drafting of legislation to revamp the American health care system, the first of three major health care bills to be voted out of committee and a significant achievement for Senator Christopher J. Dodd, Democrat of Connecticut, the acting committee chairman. Mr. Dodd has been filling in for his friend, Senator Edward M. Kennedy, Democrat of Massachusetts, who is battling brain cancer. And at various points, it seemed that Mr. Kennedy's illness had really slowed the committee's efforts to draft a health care overhaul. The committee vote, expected at 10 a.m., is expected to be strictly along party lines with Republicans unanimously in opposition. The bill includes a provision that would create a government-run health insurance program to compete with private insurers, which Republicans have generally said is a deal-breaker for them. The Republican leader, Senator Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, has said the government-run health insurance is a Trojan horse for a fully government-run system and would drive private insurers out of business. A trio of committees in the House -- Education and Labor, Energy and Commerce, and Ways and Means -- on Tuesday unveiled the full draft of their health care legislation and they are now ready to begin the public mark-up process of considering and voting on committee amendments that Mr. Dodd's panel has completed. The House legislation also includes the creation of a government-run health insurance plan. Lagging behind is the Senate Finance Committee, whose chairman, Senator Max Baucus, Democrat of Montana, has been working hardest to develop a bipartisan bill that would win the support of Republicans on his committee. Mr. Baucus and Democrats on his panel are scheduled to meet again Wednesday morning, and a meeting of top negotiators from both parties are set to meet later in the afternoon. The Finance Committee has the primary responsibility for deciding how to pay for the roughly $1 trillion, 10-year cost of the health care overhaul, and there has been serious disagreement internally among Democrats and between Democrats and Republicans over the best way to do that. A plan by Mr. Baucus to tax some employer-provided health benefits effectively collapsed last week when the Senate majority leader, Harry Reid of Nevada, and other party leaders said that there would not be sufficient support for that idea among Democrats. Mr. Baucus and Senator Olympia J. Snowe, Republican of Maine, said on Tuesday that negotiators were narrowing their focus on a menu of smaller revenue-generating ideas and hoped to reach some agreement in the days ahead. President Obama has been prodding lawmakers to pick up the pace and the pressure on Mr. Baucus is certain to escalate once Mr. Dodd's committee has approved its bill. Mr. Obama has said he would like the health care bills approved in the House and the Senate before the summer recess begins in August, so that the rival measures can be reconciled in conference in the fall. Mr. Dodd's hearing begins at 9:30 a.m. and only the acting chairman, and Senator Michael B. Enzi of Wyoming, the senior Republican on the panel are expected to speak.	2009-07-15T13:32:46+0000	None	Blogs	Web Log	521
